Post Card written to Mrs. Ida Briggs, Slayton, Minn.

Post card reads: 
Good Morning.
Dear Ida. Albert had to go to St. Paul today + will not be back til next week.  You folks come over a wk from Sun. if you can. Let me know, if you can't come if you don't while why ill look for you wk. from sunday.
Mrs. Agnes.

Note on reverse side:
"This road in earlier times was called the "State Hill."  Before highway 91 was built, this was the main transportation for going north out of town.  This was the same road that the Woold-Ridge gang used to get out of town when the robbed the bank in 1933.  About halfway up the hill they started to spread roofing nails on the road to aid thier escape.  Harvey Brux-Voort was going to grade school in Chandler at the time and remmebers after school was let out hte students went on the road and gathered up the roofing nails."

Photograph of interior of store in Chandler.  Two women are standing behind the counter, and a man standing on the other side of the counter.  This man mus be Robert Fitzpatrick.
Note on back:
"Robert Fitzpatrick was president of the State Bank of Chander longer than any other person.  He served as president f of the bank form 1918-1944.  Robert was never an empolyee of the bank.  He ran a general store for several years just was tof the old bank building.  "Fitz" was a short, rotound man with a heavy irish accent and a hearty laugh.  He liked to teas the little children and sold everything in his store from ladies gowns to "plugs" of chewing tobacco.  In the late 1910's Fitz bought a Buick car and drove it home.  It was said he never drove the car after that and always had someone shauffer him around."

Photograph of Mill Street in Currie.  Nickel Plate restaurant is on the left side.  

From Currie Independent December 1908:
The Nickel Plate Restaurant has advanced in popularity under the able and intelligent management of Mr. F. T. Winkler and his family. Besides giving meals and lunches all day and evening, they have also rooms to accommodate a limeted number and they keep for sale oysters, bread crackers, fruit, candies, etc.  They have built up a good trade and we predict for them a bright future.

The Currie Independent October 1915:
Mr. Arthur Lloyd purchased the Nickel Plate restaurant last year and has built up an excellent trade in this line.  He handles a complete lind of candies, fruits and vegetables and is open at all hours to the public.  He makes a specialty of quick lunches and has many who enjoy teh table board.  Mr. Lloyd keeps a clean and respectable place and invites your patronage.

The above cut of the Old Log Cabin at Lake Shetek is reproduced from the original negative owned and copyrighted by Miss Mame Starr, of this place and is publised by courtesy of the owner.  The negative was taken several years ago and is the only perfect reproduction of the cabin as it stood at the time of the famous outbreak of 1862.  Photographs of this negative are for sale by Miss Starr who is this year mounting the prints both in plain photograph form and also on glass in the form of small medallions.  The picture possesses historic value as well as being a thing of beauty in itself and is meeting with ready sale.

Baseball card of George Pipgras.  Big League chewing gum.  No. 12  George Pipgrass New York Yankees.  Always had plenty of speed, but never became a success as a big leaguer until he got control.  Used to be "wild as a hawk"  
   Went up to the Red Sox from the Dakaota League in1922.  Traded to the New York Yankees the next year.  Sent to minors for couple of years, then came back and won a regular place.  Pitched in three world series for the Yankees.  Last Year won 16 games and lost nine in American League.
Throws Right handed, is six foot and one and one half inches tall and weight about 150 pounds.

Aerial Photo of Lake Wilson Farmer's Coop Elevator and Lumber Co. Complex Taken in June of 1979. Left to right. Left corner old Grain elevator and mill burned April 1980 lumber yard, shingle shed and coal bunker Tornado June 1992 Farmer Omaha RR (CNWR.R) owned by Farmers Elevator. Depot destroyed by fire hall explosion Jan of 2004. Right Center Main elevator building complex. Tall elevator built 1975. Smaller Elevator, right of elevator office , built 1880's moved to this site in 1912. back grain storage annex constructed 1971. Farmer's fertilizer complex built in 1967. All 3 structured demolished in 2004.

descrip: This is a photograph. The photo is of the Murray County Bands at Valhalla on August 12 of an unidentified year. There are two to three rows of band members holding their instruments. There is a mixture of men and women in the bands. In the background is a line of trees. The photograph is in black and white. An inscription on he front, middle, bottom of the photo reads "Bands of Murray County At Valhalla - Sunday Aug. 12." There are no markings on the back of the map.
provenance: The photograph was donated by Clarice Kappes. Some of the people in the photograph are from Dovray including the donor's parents.

condnotes: The photo is slightly curled. Keep an eye one it-Polaroid photos do not stay vibrant for very long in terms of conservation.
creator: Jake Smith
descrip: This is a Polaroid photo of three inside-out tires stacked on top of one another. The smallest tire has "Planter" painted on it in white, the medium tire has "Auger Hopper" painted on it in white, and the largest tire has "Feedbunk" painted on it in white. Jake Smith of Lake Wilson built a home made tire turner to make feed bunks out of farm tires in 1982. His daughter, Janet Smith Timmerman painted on the words in the photo and dubbed the machine "Big Bertha." The machine made a very loud noise when it was operated and drew the attention of neighbors.

caption: Front
condnotes: The photo is fairly curled but this may be fixed in storage. Damage to the edges, corners, and back.
descrip: This is a picture of Herbert and Oran Jones operating a 1919 John Deere threshing machine in 1920. In the background is a large pile of straw and a cart in the foreground are the threshing machine, the two men and another cart. The photo is in black and white.
notes: The four photos in this accession were taken on a farm located in Section 4, Lowville Township, Murray County, on the banks of Bear Lake. Evan Jones, father to Herbert Jones and grandfather to Oran Jones, moved to this farm in 1879. The first Post Office was located on this property. Evan was the post office manger until the closing of the post office in 1900. The contents of the post office were taken to the post office in Balaton, MN. Herbert Jones took over the operation of the farm in the early 1900s. At that time the farm was located on the west banks f Bear Lake. The following decade and a half there was great interest in the drainage of the Great Oasis which also included the drainage of Bear Lake. As a result of the drainage of the Lake, Herbert was able to increase his acreage of farm operation by about 267 acres. One of the first major crops that Herbert planted on this "new" fertile land was timothy. The production per acre was great and as a result provided new opportunities for the family.
people:
Dennis B. Miller
Oran Jones
Herbert Jones
Evan Jones
provenance: On the photo is written "Oran & Dad 1920" This is referring to Oran Jones and his father Herbert Jones. It is believed by the donor that this picture of the threshing machine owned by Herbert Jones were with the timothy production based upon the large pile of straw prevalent in the picture. Herbert purchased a Republic truck during this time and hauled the timothy production to the Lake Wilson elevator.

descrip: This is a class photo of a Lake Wilson School class. The photo is in black and white. There are three rows of students and the teacher sitting in the middle of the middle row. Judging from the students, it appears to be a elementary class, somewhere between 2-4 grade. Judging from their appearance alone there are ten girls, one woman, and fourteen boys.
provenance: According to a note by the donor she believes the teacher may be Mrs. Fowser and the fourth boy in the first row "looks like a Buse."
sterms:
Buse 
Mrs. Fowser

condnotes: The photo is curling and coming away from the paper. The list of names has completely fallen off the paper.
descrip: This is a photo of the third and fourth grade classes of the lake Wilson School sometime between 1950 and 1960. The picture is in black an white. The picture is glued onto a piece of white paper. A kist along with the picture lists all the students: R. Hurd, L. Scotting, L. Severeid, E. Suedkamp, P. Timmerman, P. Powell, C. Tutt, Mrs. Hook, D. Kalas, L. Vogel, S. McCullum, L. Reese, J. Packard, P. Stabb, J. Mihin, D. Nepp, R. Scotting, S. Ruina, V. Watson, S. Scotting, J. Sierk, L. Scotting, K. Malmquist, and T. Sabin. There are three rows of students. Looking at physical features alone there appears to be eleven boys, one woman, and nine girls.

condnotes: There are a couple finger print marks on the negative.
descrip: This is a set of two photo negatives. The negatives depict Ralph D. Mizner in his Korean War military uniform. The negatives are connected together in one sheet.
provenance: Ralph Mizner was born September 7, 1926 in Slayton. He served in the Marine Corps during WWII, the Korean War, and the Vietnam War. Received the Purple Heart twice. Ralph married Terri Mizner. The couple had three children: Lynn, Mark, and Terry.
sterms:
Ralph Mizner
Mary Mattson
Military personnel
World War II
War
Korean War
Vietnam War
